commit.message: enable wheel generation
whole cookie invalid when Cookie() is called with invalid value
version bump

don't allow domain dot to affect comparison

If you want to know if there is an initial domain dot,
then check the value yourself rather than comparing
to another cookie, there is no semantic difference between
cookie domains with a dot vs. without, and this is not just
the RFC but how User-Agents actually use the attribute

prevent .domain in Set-Cookie renders

Even if we are going to accept this junk in parses for users,
and as a matter of necessity also allow it to exist on Cookie objects,
and even if the User-Agent is obligated to ignore the dot anyway,
we should NOT be generating this RFC-invalid output by default.

declare initial dot domains valid by fiat

This really, really sucks. But I am very aggressively not allowing
attribute values I define as invalid to exist on Cookie objects,
which prevents even temporarily checking if there is an initial dot.
Domain names with initial dot are NOT RFC valid and we shouldn't
produce them, but we might want to see them so they are "valid"
as far as that goes.

Merge pull request #6 from ngo/master

MAX_AGE_AV regexp: account for Max-Age=0

MAX_AGE_AV regexp: account for Max-Age=0

Some of the web frameworks (e.g. Plone) use the following trick to clear cookies after logout:
Set-Cookie: auth=deleted; Max-Age=0 
cookies.py currently chokes in those cases because the RFC forbids that (the leading digit must be non-zero).

add 3.4 and drop 3.1 (tox/pip breakage)

A backward-incompatible version bump comes with this.

None of the supporting test tools seem to actually support it any more
and those regressions show no signs of being fixed. 3.1 is a royal pain
anyway, not important in any distro I know of, and it was going to happen
someday, so why not now.
3.1 may still work, I'm just not interested in implied guarantees when
testing it is such a pain.

Sequenced this after _cookie_class so that can be in the new version

add new ways to change Cookies' Cookie class

This was spurred by a suggestion by Laurent Bachelier (thanks, Laurent).

For those just tuning in, Cookies is an class which offers dict-like access to
collections of Cookie objects, each representing a name/value pair with its own
attributes (corresponding to attributes of an HTTP Cookie).

To make a cookie collection which constructs instances using your own class
(suppose it is called Scone) - use Cookies(_cookie_class=Scone).

To make a Cookies subclass generating instances which do the same thing,
override DEFAULT_COOKIE_CLASS on the subclass itself, and instantiate it
as normal.

It's also still possible to use the lower-level API to make whatever collection
interface you really want to use, if your requirements are really different.

get rid of \r\n in output from Cookies.render_*

This is a backward-incompatible change.

Now render_request defaults to what you'd normally want ("; ".join)
for a Cookie: header, while render_response returns a list of
the values you'd want for separate Set-Cookie headers (there is no safe
way of combining Set-Cookie headers without ambiguity, and it isn't
allowed in RFC 6265). The combine= parameter is no more.

By default, values are sorted to give more deterministic output.
Pass sort=False to skip this step (and let me know if it makes any
real performance difference for you).

This should be more versatile in general, more specifically friendly
to uses in a WSGI environment and should clean up the API guide some.
Generating raw HTTP responses is a less frequent requirement (e.g.
nobody much uses CGI now) and doing it from the new output is cleaner
than it was to do the usual cases by splitting strings, etc.
Add Python 3.3 to supported/tested versions.

accept empty cookie values in parsing

These are quite useful as a fallback when a server is trying to
force-expire cookies with a client that ignores Expires. Such a client
may happily send back the empty values, resulting in a gratuitous raise.
If these should be rejected it should be at a higher level.
correct mistake in README with this version's render_request behavior

Cookies.get_all() for picking up duplicate cookies

This is not a reliable way to move data back and forth from the client; nor
will it be extremely fast when there are huge number of cookies. It is for
rarer technical or security purposes, e.g. detecting added cookies.

remove unnecessary/annoying prefix= arg

in most contexts this library might be used (e.g. CGI/WSGI environ)
it is quite annoying to have to suppress the default prefix,
and it hurts the API's simplicity. I used to worry that this would
help perpetuate confusion about the difference between request and
response formats but this isn't the right way to fix that.

since this breaks backward compatibility with scripts that specify
prefix=, I am incrementing the major version.
